            <label key="27f85a4ce0cedf38cde6fff33e7fa2ef">
                <text>Extinction Risk </text>
            </label>
            <label key="48d33a14032d9c43b0228be46a25fef6">
                <text>Extinction risk is not as well studied in reptiles as it is within other animal groups, such as many bird and mammal species.  </text>
            </label>
            <label key="c4d5820bcd587d1884ab5a28a23c8501">
                <text>The graph shows the extinction risk in some major groups of vertebrates.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="c86b24652ba9291f6a66de9c11ce9ebf">
                <text>Some species are described as ‘data deficient’. Even if an organism is well known, the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) defines a species as being data deficient 'when there is inadequate information to make a direct, or indirect, assessment of its risk of extinction based on its distribution and/or population status'.</text>
            </label>
